# üíº LinkedIn Learning Post  
*(Professional + beginner-friendly)*

**Post Text:**

> üöÄ **Day 8 ‚Äì Learning Ansible Installation (Global vs User-Specific)**  
>  
> Today I learned an important DevOps concept while working on a hands-on lab:  
> **Installing Ansible globally vs for a specific user**.  
>  
> üîπ **Global Installation**  
> - Installed using `sudo pip3 install ansible==4.7.0`  
> - Binary available in `/usr/local/bin`  
> - All users can run Ansible commands  
> - Ideal for dedicated Jump Hosts and automation controllers  
>  
> üîπ **User-Specific Installation**  
> - Installed using `pip3 install --user ansible==4.7.0`  
> - Binary available in `~/.local/bin`  
> - Only the specific user can access Ansible  
> - Useful for shared systems and restricted environments  
>  
> üí° **Key takeaway:**  
> Always follow the task or production requirement carefully.  
> If it says *‚ÄúAnsible must be available globally‚Äù*, a user-level install is not enough.  
>  
> This small detail makes a big difference in real-world DevOps automation setups.  
>  
